3","1435":"1435","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Biddenden, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1415–1435":"1415–1435","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1395–1420":"1395–1420","1390–Female":"1390–Deceased","1415":"1415","1503":"1503","1435":"1435","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"O’Sullivan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Munster): Anglicized form of Gaelic Ó Súileabháin ‘descendant of <i>Súileabháin</i>’ (  see  Sullivan  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Sullivan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam, Donal, James Patrick, Michael Patrick, Aileen, Brigid, Paddy, Siobhan, John Patrick, Kevin Patrick, Parnell.","Irish (Cork and Kerry): shortened form of   O'Sullivan  ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Jane O’Sullivan was born in 1415, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Peter O'Sullivan, was 20 and her mother, O'Sullivan, was 26. She had at least 2 daughters with John Lucas II. She died in 1435, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1415–1435":"1415–1435","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1395–1420":"1395–1420","1390–Female":"1390–Surnud","1415":"1415","1503":"1503","1435":"1435","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Biddenden, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1415–1435":"1415–1435","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1395–1420":"1395–1420","1390–Female":"1390–Kuollut","1415":"1415","1503":"1503","1435":"1435","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Biddenden, Kent, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, England","England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1415–1435":"1415–1435","1410–1474":"1410–1474","1435–1503":"1435–1503","1395–1420":"1395–1420","1390–Female":"1390–Décédée","1415":"1415","1503":"1503","1435":"1435","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1474":"1474","1395":"1395","1390":"1390","Biddenden, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Biddenden, Kent, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Benenden, Kent, England":"Benenden, Kent, Angleterre","England, United Kingdom":"A